### Chi-squared Test
## this is how you create a data frame
df <- data.frame(row.names = c("Protected", "Unprotected"),
                 HHC = c(26, 1), 
                 NIA = c(1, 29))

## this is how you create a matrix
mat <- matrix(c(26, 1, 1, 29),
              ncol = 2, nrow = 2,
              dimnames = list(c("Protected", "Unprotected"),
                              c("HHC", "NIA")))

## testing for significance
chi <- chisq.test(df)
chi
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  df
## X-squared = 45.602, df = 1, p-value = 1.449e-11
chi$expected
##                  HHC      NIA
## Protected   12.78947 14.21053
## Unprotected 14.21053 15.78947
chi$observed
##             HHC NIA
## Protected    26   1
## Unprotected   1  29

### T-test

## load data
mpa <- read.csv("~/Desktop/Plymouth University/PALS/mpa.csv")

## data wrangling
coral <- mpa$coral
status <- mpa$status
site <- mpa$site
depth <- mpa$depth
lat <- mpa$lat
lon <- mpa$lon

## visualise data
par(mfrow = c(2,1))
hist(coral)
boxplot(coral, horizontal = T)

par(mfrow = c(1,1))

## statistical analyses
# testing if assumptions of normality and homogeneity are correct (a priori)
shapiro.test(coral) # data are non-normal
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  coral
## W = 0.89983, p-value = 0.00613
require(car)
## Loading required package: car
leveneTest(coral~status) # data are barely homogenous
## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = median)
##       Df F value  Pr(>F)  
## group  1  3.4645 0.07252 .
##       30                  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
# a transformation is required
sqrtcoral <- sqrt(coral)
hist(sqrtcoral)

shapiro.test(sqrtcoral) # data are normally distributed
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  sqrtcoral
## W = 0.98003, p-value = 0.8005
leveneTest(sqrtcoral~status) # data are clearly homogenous
## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = median)
##       Df F value Pr(>F)
## group  1  0.0053 0.9425
##       30
# the transformation solved our problem!

# let's proceed with a ttest
t.test(sqrtcoral~status)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  sqrtcoral by status
## t = 5.4354, df = 29.995, p-value = 6.817e-06
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  1.054364 2.323596
## sample estimates:
##     mean in group MPA mean in group Non-MPA 
##              3.466541              1.777561
# t = 5.44, df = 30, p < 0.001 > the protected area has significantly higher coral cover  


# calculating descriptive statistics the old way
m <- tapply(sqrtcoral, list(status), mean)
n <- tapply(sqrtcoral, list(status), length)
sd <- tapply(sqrtcoral, list(status), sd)
se <- sd/sqrt(n)

# calculating descriptive statistics the fast way
library(psych)
## 
## Attaching package: 'psych'

stats <- describeBy(sqrtcoral, list(status), mat = T, digits = 2)

# evidently, only protection status has an influence on healthy Scleractinia cover!


### Analysis of variance (ANOVA)
# used when more than two levels are compared

## statistical analysis
anova <- aov(sqrtcoral~site) # testing for differences between the four sites
summary(anova) # there are significant differences (p < 0.001), but where?
##             Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## site         3  23.16   7.720   9.465 0.000176 ***
## Residuals   28  22.84   0.816                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
# we need a post-hoc test (a posteriori)
TukeyHSD(anova)
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = sqrtcoral ~ site)
## 
## $site
##                    diff        lwr        upr     p adj
## Manta-Bamboo  1.6587082  0.4258459  2.8915704 0.0052226
## Moray-Bamboo  1.8922244  0.6593622  3.1250867 0.0013606
## Tabon-Bamboo  0.1729728 -1.0598895  1.4058350 0.9804894
## Moray-Manta   0.2335162 -0.9993460  1.4663785 0.9542842
## Tabon-Manta  -1.4857354 -2.7185977 -0.2528731 0.0135868
## Tabon-Moray  -1.7192517 -2.9521139 -0.4863894 0.0037034
# there are significant differences between all sites except Tabon and Bamboo
# as well as Moray and Manta, with p = 0.98 and p = 0.95, respectively
# this result provides further evidence for the hypothesis: the locations that are protected
# are not significantly different from one another and those that are not are also not
# significantly different from one another
